To create a simple search bar in PHP, we will follow these steps:

1. **HTML for the search form**: We'll start with basic HTML to structure our form where the user can input their search query.
2. **PHP code to handle the search request**: This is where we'll capture the search term from the form submission, execute a search query based on this term, and display the results (which, for simplicity, will be hard-coded but should ideally connect to a database).
3. **Displaying search results**: We will show how to output the searched items.

### Step 1: HTML for the Search Form

First, we create an HTML form with a single input field where users can type in their search term.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Search Bar</title>
</head>
<body>

<h2>Search Bar Example</h2>

<form action="" method="get">
    <input type="search" id="searchTerm" name="searchTerm" placeholder="Type to search...">
    <button type="submit">Search</button>
</form>

<?php
// PHP code will go here
?>

</body>
</html>
```

### Step 2: PHP Code to Handle the Search Request

In this step, we capture the `searchTerm` from the form submission and use it to display some (in this case, hard-coded) search results. We'll also add basic error handling.

```php
<?php
if(isset($_GET['searchTerm'])) {
    $searchTerm = $_GET['searchTerm'];

    // Basic check for empty string
    if(empty($searchTerm)) {
        echo 'Please enter a term to search.';
    } else {
        // Display results (in real application, connect to database here)
        $results = array(
            "Result 1",
            "Result 2",
            "Result 3"
        );

        echo '<h3>Search Results for: ' . $searchTerm . '</h3>';
        foreach ($results as $result) {
            echo '<p>' . $result . '</p>';
        }
    }
}
?>
```

### Putting It All Together

Here's the complete PHP and HTML code combined:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Search Bar</title>
</head>
<body>

<h2>Search Bar Example</h2>

<form action="" method="get">
    <input type="search" id="searchTerm" name="searchTerm" placeholder="Type to search...">
    <button type="submit">Search</button>
</form>

<?php
if(isset($_GET['searchTerm'])) {
    $searchTerm = $_GET['searchTerm'];

    // Basic check for empty string
    if(empty($searchTerm)) {
        echo 'Please enter a term to search.';
    } else {
        // Display results (in real application, connect to database here)
        $results = array(
            "Result 1",
            "Result 2",
            "Result 3"
        );

        echo '<h3>Search Results for: ' . $searchTerm . '</h3>';
        foreach ($results as $result) {
            echo '<p>' . $result . '</p>';
        }
    }
}
?>

</body>
</html>
```

This example is a simplified demonstration of creating a search bar using PHP. In a real-world application, you would likely use a database to store data and implement more robust error handling and security measures, such as sanitizing user input.

